{
  "texts": [
    "In contrast, combining (HFFA) with Class F FA at 5% to 15% replacement levels led to microstructural deterioration, with a 30% increase in porosity, significant cracking, and a 20% reduction in density, which reduced durability [59].",
    "Kanthe et al. [61] showed that replacing cement with RHA at levels between 10 and 50% reduced water absorption by 6% when superplasticizers were added, directly correlating with improved durability by limiting the penetration of harmful substances.",
    "The study also found that RHA increased resistance to acid attack, reducing mass loss to 0.07% at a 10% replacement compared to 0.35% in the control mix.",
    "Additionally, Sakr et al. [64] reported that RHA enhances durability by increasing sulfate attack resistance and reducing permeability.",
    "This is attributed to the pozzolanic reaction of RHA, which creates a denser microstructure and forms more calcium silicate hydrate (C-S-H) gel, a critical component for resisting chemical attacks and reducing permeability."
  ]
}